signals.config_analysis_detail.151757745.title: Node pool autoscaling limits reached
signals.config_analysis_detail.151757745.text: The 'default-pool' node pool in the 'gke-cluster-123' cluster is configured with autoscaling enabled, a minimum node count of 1, and a maximum node count of 10. The nodepool's `initialNodeCount` is set to 10. If the current number of nodes is already at the maximum (10), the node pool will not scale up further, regardless of the demand. The nodepool was last updated at 2025-07-16 00:34:53 PDT.

signals.correlated_event_detail.db760515.title: Cluster Autoscaler: No Scale Down
signals.correlated_event_detail.db760515.text: The Cluster Autoscaler logs indicate that it was unable to scale down nodes in the 'default-pool' nodepool of the 'gke-cluster-123' cluster. The reason provided is 'no.scale.down.node.no.place.to.move.pods', suggesting that there were no suitable nodes to which the pods could be moved. This could potentially block the autoscaler from scaling up the cluster if it needs to remove nodes to make room for new ones, and is relevant to the reported symptom of the nodepool not scaling up.

details.summary: The mentioned node cannot scale down as there are existing pods on the node which cannot be moved. If customer wants autoscaler to scale down this node, they should modify the pod(s) spec on their YAML to allow it to move to another node.

signals.correlated_event_detail.e87eeba1.title: Nodepool Scaling Issues: IP Exhaustion & Template Missing
signals.correlated_event_detail.e87eeba1.text: The 'default-pool' nodepool in GKE cluster 'gke-cluster-123' experienced scaling issues. Attempts to resize the nodepool to 10 nodes were initiated around 03:39 and 05:53 UTC, but a node upgrade operation failed at 05:21 UTC due to two primary reasons: missing instance templates ('gke-gke-cluster-123-default-pool-00555e95' and 'gke-gke-cluster-123-default-pool-92e2a866') and IP address exhaustion within the 'small-subnet-009-8' subnet. The error message indicates insufficient free IP addresses in the range '10.116.1.0/29', suggesting the subnet needs expansion or an alternative IP range should be selected.

diagnostics.gke_ca_no_scale_up.0.title: Node provisioning couldn't scale because auto proviosning is not enabled
diagnostics.gke_ca_no_scale_up.0.text:
Node auto provisioning in the cluster `gke-cluster-123` within the project `test-project` and located in `us-east4`  couldn't scale up because node auto provisioning is not enabled at cluster level.

If node auto-provisioning is disabled, new nodes won't be automatically provisioned if the pending Pod has requirements that can't be satisfied by any existing node pools.

For more details, please refer to logs in [Logs Explorer](https://console.cloud.google.com/logs/query;query=resource.type%3D%22k8s_cluster%22%0Aresource.labels.location%3D%22us-east4%22%0Aresource.labels.cluster_name%3D%22gke-cluster-123%22%0Alog_id%2528%22container.googleapis.com%2Fcluster-autoscaler-visibility%22%2529%0A%2528jsonPayload.noDecisionStatus.noScaleUp.reason.messageId%3D%22no.scale.up.nap.disabled%22%20OR%20jsonPayload.noDecisionStatus.noScaleUp.napFailureReason.messageId%3D%22no.scale.up.nap.disabled%22%20OR%20jsonPayload.noDecisionStatus.noScaleUp.skippedMigs.reason.messageId%3D%22no.scale.up.nap.disabled%22%20OR%20jsonPayload.noDecisionStatus.noScaleUp.unhandledPodGroups.napFailureReasons.messageId%3D%22no.scale.up.nap.disabled%22%20OR%20jsonPayload.noDecisionStatus.noScaleUp.unhandledPodGroups.rejectedMigs.reason.messageId%3D%22no.scale.up.nap.disabled%22%2529;duration=P3D?project=test-project)

For mitigation, please review the cluster configuration and consider [enabling node auto-provisioning](https://cloud.google.com/kubernetes-engine/docs/how-to/node-auto-provisioning#enable).

conclusion.hypothesis.ip_address_exhaust.title: IP Address Exhaustion
conclusion.hypothesis.ip_address_exhaust.text:
### Overview:
The 'default-pool' nodepool in your GKE cluster 'gke-cluster-123' is failing to scale up due to IP address exhaustion within the 'small-subnet-009-8' subnet. The cluster autoscaler logs also show "scale.up.error.ip.space.exhausted" errors, indicating that the cluster lacks sufficient unallocated IP address space to add new nodes or pods.

### Recommended fixes:
*   **Expand the IP range of the 'small-subnet-009-8' subnet**.  Refer to the documentation on expanding subnets.
*   **Consider using a different IP range** for the nodepool.
*   **Reduce the number of pods per node** to free up IP addresses. You can achieve this by creating a new node pool with a smaller maximum number of pods per node and migrating workloads to that node pool.
*   **Review IP address planning** to ensure the node IP address range aligns with your scaling requirements.

conclusion.hypothesis.cluster_autoscaler.title: Cluster Autoscaler Unable to Scale Down
conclusion.hypothesis.cluster_autoscaler.text:
### Overview:
The Cluster Autoscaler logs indicate that it was unable to scale down nodes in the 'default-pool' nodepool of the 'gke-cluster-123' cluster because there were no suitable nodes to which the pods could be moved. This can block the autoscaler from scaling up the cluster if it needs to remove nodes to make room for new ones.

### Recommended fixes:
*   **Review the scheduling requirements of the Pods** on the underutilized node to determine if they can be moved to another node in the cluster.
*   **Check for any PodDisruptionBudgets** that might be preventing the pods from being evicted.
*   **Ensure that there are other nodes in the cluster** that meet the scheduling requirements of the pods on the underutilized node.

conclusion.hypothesis.node_auto-provisio.title: Node Auto-Provisioning Disabled
conclusion.hypothesis.node_auto-provisio.text:
### Overview:
The 'default-pool' nodepool in your GKE cluster 'gke-cluster-123' is not scaling up because node auto-provisioning is disabled at the cluster level. When node auto-provisioning is disabled, GKE cannot automatically create new node pools to satisfy the resource requirements of pending pods.

### Recommended fixes:
*   Enable node auto-provisioning for your cluster. You can find instructions on how to do this in the GKE documentation.
